column4: Definition
Sports where athletes are judged by an external person on the aesthetics of their performance.
Gentle gymnastics combining deep breathing and slow movements, aimed at strengthening postural muscles to develop the body in a harmonious way
Spiritual and physical discipline derived from this method, aimed at freeing the mind from the body's constraints through the mastery of movement, rhythm, and breath

Dynamic and demanding form of yoga that synchronizes breathing with a progressive series of postures. Ashtanga Is organised around six series of progressively demanding postures. These series are designed not only to strengthen the body but also to increase flexibility. Mysore practice, the hallmark of this discipline, emphasises students' independence while following a traditional pattern of movement.
Physical and sports activity aimed at developing muscle mass for aesthetic purposes
Activity of leading the crowd in shouting encouragement and supporting a team at a sports event. The activity involves chanting, gymnastics, dance and teamwork
The activity of moving your feet and body to music

A type of dancing where carefully organized movements tell a story or express an idea, or a theatre work that uses this type of dancing: Dancers often wear elaborate costumes and pointe shoes, which allow them to dance on the tips of their toes

A dance style focused on expression and improvisation, characterized by lighter, more fluid movements. This art form incorporates ballet techniques but is primarily influenced by modern dance, including floor movements, improvisation, and an aerial quality

A multifaceted dance that blends various cultural influences, including Islamic, Andalusian, Gypsy, Sephardic, and Arab traditions. It combines elements of singing, guitar playing, dancing, and hand clapping
Traditional Spanish dances characterized by a groups of dance origins from different regions of Spain (Flamenco, Sevillanas, Sardana, Jota, Fandango, Paso Doble, Bolero, Muñeira)
A popular free dance style that combines elements of performance art, release technique, and improvisation
Type of dance in which the rhythm is kept by the noise of the dancer's shoes on the floor
Dance performance describe magnificently costumed male and female shamans who sing and dance to musical accompaniment, drawing the heavenly spirits down to earth through their performance
A style of dance in which the choreography is based on classical dance but with a few modifications such as angular positions, broken joints, off-axis, parallels

Street dance, combining elements of modern dance, tap dance, and swing. It is most often performed to hip-hop music and includes a wide range of freestyle movements, with three main styles: breakdancing, popping, and locking.

Kathak is one of the eight forms of classical Indian dance from northern India. It is primarily a form of theatre, with instrumental and vocal music and the use of stylised gestures and movements to represent the story being told. Its current form contains traces of Hindu temple dances and rituals, with influence from the bhakti movement
Traditional dance style from Ireland, characterized by quick footwork and a stiff upper body

Refers to the various dance styles of sub-Saharan Africa. These dances are closely connected with the traditional rhythms and music traditions of the region. African dance uses the concepts of polyrhythm and total body articulation. African dances are a collective activity performed in large groups, with significant interaction between dancers and onlookers in the majority of styles
Type of dancing that is popular in musical theatre, combines ability to sing, dance and act
Street dance combining sport and art. It takes the form of battles between individuals or teams. The dancers take it in turns to perform a series of leg movements and figures on the floor

A dance form that has evolved over the centuries to give rise to different styles such as Romantic and Neoclassical ballet. Classical dancers must master basic positions such as pliés, tendus and dégagés. Pointes, special shoes, allow dancers to dance on tiptoe, requiring exceptional balance, strength and flexibility

Sport in which divers are required to perform acrobatic figures at a height of 1, 3 or 10m. Can be practised individually or in synchronised pairs. Judged on both difficulty and quality of execution in space. These figures are classified in order of difficulty.

A drill team can be one of four different entities: (a) A military drill team is a marching unit that performs routines based on military foot or exhibition drills. Military drill teams perform either armed or unarmed ; (b) dance drill team creates routines based on precision dance movements rather than military drill. These teams usually do not carry anything, but may use props in field production numbers. They may perform to recorded music, or the live music of an accompanying marching band ; (c) a team that execute routines carrying either one or multiple flags or pom-poms. This team's movements are also based in dance and may also have a heavy influence of gymnastics as well. These teams also may perform to music, either live or recorded ; (d) a team that is mounted (horse, motorcycle, etc.) or advances some type of mobile object (library carts, lawn chairs, or even garbage bins). May also include teams of dogs and handlers.

A sport practised on ice with skates, combining acrobatics and precision of movement. It is practised individually or in pairs. Technical elements such as jumps and spins are highly recognisable and punctuate the choreography

Sport practised on ice with skates. At the higher levels, competition is divided into two segments: the short program, which is skated first, and the free skate. The short program features required elements which include jump elements, spin elements and a step sequence. The free skate, the second and longer segment of competition, features a broader set of requirements and a maximum number of elements a skater may perform. If a skater performs more than the number of well-balanced program elements permitted, there are no deductions, but the skater will not receive credit for these additional elements. After a skater completes his or her free skate and receives a free skate score, that score is added to the short program score to determine overall standings.

The pairs event combines the athleticism of singles skating with the challenge of unison and the acrobatics of overhead lifts and throws. Like singles skating, pairs competitions include a short program and a free skate, with each segment receiving a technical score and a component score, and the team with the most points overall is named the winner. The pairs short program consists of several required elements including lifts, side-by-side solo jumps done in unison, throw jumps, a step sequence and a death spiral. The free skate consists of technical skills and choreography that show off the strengths of the team. Shadow skating (in which partners perform identical maneuvers some distance apart) and mirror skating (in which the pair’s moves are in opposite directions and mirror each other) are aspects of pairs skating and contribute to the overall effect of a program.

Synchronized skating is a team sport in which eight to 20 skaters perform a program together in unison. It uses the same judging system as singles, pairs and ice dance, and is characterized by teamwork, speed, intricate formations and challenging step sequences. As with the other disciplines, competition at the higher levels include two competition segments: a short program with required elements and a free skate. Elements in synchronized skating include blocks, circles, wheels, lines, intersections, move elements, creative elements, no holds elements, spins and pairs maneuvers.

Like pairs skating, ice dance features a male and female skating in unison, but instead of performing jump and spin elements, the team completes difficult dance patterns, step sequences and maneuvers while showcasing exceptional interpretation of music and precise steps. The ice dance competition consists of two segments: a rhythm dance and a free dance. The rhythm dance features required elements, including lifts, step sequences and pre-determined dance patterns performed to a specific rhythm of music within a required tempo range. The free dance, like the rhythm dance, features step sequences, lifts and a broad selection of difficult skating skills, but the team skates to a music and tempo of their choosing, with a goal of pulling off an entertaining, moving and inspiring performance that looks effortless despite its difficulty. Innovative choreography, timing and rhythm are paramount. After the second segment of competition, the scores from the rhythm dance and free dance are added together to determine overall placement.

Synchronized team skating, also known as precision skating, consists of a team of 8 or more skaters (in the United States) or 12 or more skaters (in Canada) who perform various movements, synchronized with at least part of the team. Skating elements include formations such as circles, lines, blocks, and wheels. Spirals are allowed, but jumps of more than one revolution are not. Lifts are also not permitted.

A sport discipline performed with quad roller skates on a smooth and flat surface measuring at least 20 x 40 meters (parquet, smooth concrete, terrazzo, etc.). It can be practiced individually or in pairs. This is a technical and acrobatic discipline that requires speed, power, precision, and artistic expression. Athletes can compete in compulsory figures or free skating.
Each event is judged separately. An athlete participating in both events will also receive a combined ranking.
A discipline that refers to a set of physical activities aimed at helping the practitioner improve their physical fitness and lifestyle, with a focus on overall well-being.

A discipline combining fitness and acrobatics. It allows you to demonstrate your ability to perform a series of dynamic movements to music. A truly creative discipline, it requires you to capture the audience's attention and harmoniously combine dance elements with elements of difficulty. Movements can be performed individually, in duets, trios or groups (5 gymnasts).
A discipline practiced by repeating sequences of light-to-moderate intensity activities over extended periods of time.
A set of physical exercises, performed with or without apparatus and light equipment, aimed at stretching, developing, or rehabilitating the body.

A discipline in which gymnasts perform a series of acrobatics on a dynamic track. The Tumbling track is 25 meters long and 2 meters wide. Gymnasts must perform a sequence of 8 consecutive acrobatic moves, ending with a "dismount." The landing area measures 6 meters by 4 meters.

Sport practised to music using apparatus: hoop, ball, clubs, ribbon and rope. In competition, it can be practised either individually or in a group of 5 gymnasts. It is a complete discipline combining flexibility, grace and skill.

An acrobatic discipline that can be practiced individually or in pairs (called synchronized). Gymnasts perform on a trampoline measuring 4 meters by 2 meters, positioned 1.15 meters above the ground. 120 springs surrounding the trampoline allow the gymnasts to reach a height of up to 8 meters. The exercises consist of 10 trampoline touches, during which gymnasts can perform numerous acrobatic moves (jumps, flips, twists, etc.). These acrobatics must be performed in succession.

A sport that combines acrobatics and choreography performed individually and collectively, to music. Pyramids are the special feature of this discipline. It requires strength, flexibility, agility and acrobatic skills. The exercises are performed on a platform similar to that used in artistic gymnastics.

A discipline combining fitness and acrobatics. It requires strength, endurance, and flexibility. Gymnasts perform to music lasting 1 minute 30 seconds on a surface of 7 x 7 meters for individuals, and 10 x 10 meters for groups. The movements can be performed individually, in pairs, in trios, or in groups (5 gymnasts).

A discipline for women practiced on 4 apparatus: the vault, the uneven bars, the balance beam, and the floor. The combination of these 4 apparatuses makes it a very complete discipline. For men, it is practiced on 6 apparatus: the floor, the pommel horse, the rings, the vault, the parallel bars, and the high bar.

Show jumping consists of a rider and his horse completing a series of obstacles in the allotted time, without knocking over any bars. The type of obstacle, the angles and the turns are varied, and it's up to the rider to adapt by modifying the speed, amplitude, impulsion and trajectory of his horse to make the course a success.

Artistic swimming, formerly known as synchronised swimming, is the closest thing to dancing in the water. Athletes must be synchronised to a single choreography, linking technical figures, artistic effects and acrobatic stunts: somersaults, twists and splits.

This discipline is performed on a circus stage 13.5 metres in diameter, surrounded by stands. Individuals perform as clowns, trapeze artists, jugglers, tightrope walkers, trainers, magicians and contortionists, as well as tightrope walkers on ladders and bicycles, and acrobats on the ground, in the air or on horseback, hanging from a cloth or clinging to a Chinese pole.

A circus discipline with two distinct components: figures on the ground, where the acrobat uses his or her body to perform figures (contortions, jumps, balances, stunts, etc.) on the ground. This practice is similar to artistic gymnastics. Aerial acrobatics refers to all acrobatic exercises performed at height. Several aerial apparatus are used in this discipline, including the hoop, the corde lisse, the trapeze and the fabric.
Skill discipline that consists in its strictest sense of continuously throwing, catching and re-throwing objects in the air.

Balancing is the art of balancing. It involves performing technical feats by stabilising your body in incredible positions. The discipline can be performed with specific objects such as the balancing ball, stilts, the rolla bolla, the unicycle or the tightrope (funambulism).
Sports in which a high strength-to-mass ratio has typically been seen to enhance performance
column5: Watts et al. (2003) ; Novoa-Vignau et al. (2017)

column4: Sport practised from a boat propelled by a paddle, in calm water, at sea and in white water.

A sporting discipline that includes a variety of climbing activities: bouldering, rock climbing and speed climbing. Each discipline has its own technical rules and regulations, which vary depending on where the activity is practised.
Discipline qui consiste à gravir des voies constituées de roches naturelles dans un environnement extérieur.
Sport practised in a boat propelled by a double paddle. A kayak for flatwater racing is propelled by one, two or four paddlers. In slalom and downriver racing, it is used by a single paddler.
The sport of balancing on a board carried by a breaking wave.

Disciplines in which participants interact primarily with a game object designed to be thrown, hit, caught or manipulated according to precise rules. The object may be a ball, disc, spinner or any other object designed for this purpose.
Discipline played with two teams of seven players each and a disc (Frisbee). The players pass the disc back and forth across the field to land it in the opponent's goal.

Racquet sport played between two players (singles) or two pairs (doubles) in two half-courts separated by a net. The players, known as badminton players, score points by hitting a shuttlecock with a racket into the opponent's court. The game ends as soon as the shuttlecock hits the ground or gets caught in the net.

Discipline played especially in North America by two teams of nine players, in which a player hits a ball with a bat (= stick) and tries to run around four bases on a large field before the other team returns the ball
Team sport played on a rectangular court, in which two teams of five players play against each other and try to score by throwing the ball into the opponent's basket.

Discipline adaptation of the able-bodied basketball version in wheelchair. The object of the game is to score the most points in the opposing team’s basket. The team with the most points by the time the clock expires wins.

Discipline in which two teams of six players, four players or two players, separated by a net of varying height depending on the level and category, play against each other by kicking a ball back and forth with their hands or forearms over a horizontally stretched net on a rectangular pitch 18 m long and 9 m wide or 16 m long and 7 m wide, depending on the category.

Discipline in which two teams of two players compete on an outdoor sand court measuring 8x16m, separated by a net, with a ball that they throw back and forth using their hands or feet.  A match is played in 2 winning sets of 21 points (+ a tie-break of 15 points).
Italian dscipline played outside on a court made of soil, in which the players roll a large ball as close as possible to a smaller ball

Batting and ball sport played between two teams of 11 players. The game is played on a cricket pitch, with a 20-metre pitch in the centre. There are two wickets at either end of the pitch. Cricket is a popular game, the aim of which is to score the most runs.

Discipline in which two teams of five players and a goalkeeper compete in three 20-minute periods. This indoor discipline is played without skates in a 40x20m gymnasium. The aim is to put the ball into the opponent's goal using a stick.

Sport in which two teams of eleven players each compete on a rectangular pitch between 90 and 120 metres long and between 45 and 90 metres wide. The aim is to kick a spherical ball into the opponent's goal using the feet, head or any other part of the body (except the hand or arm).

Discipline involving two teams of 4 players and a goalkeeper. Played indoors on a pitch measuring a minimum of 25 metres and a maximum of 42 metres. To score, the players have to hit the ball into the opponent's net. Unlike football, the ball is smaller, heavier and less bouncy. The match is played in two 20- or 25-minute halves, with a break of no more than 15 minutes between each half. The teams are entitled to a non-cumulative one-minute time-out in each of the two periods.

Discipline in which two teams of seven players play on a rectangular pitch measuring 40 metres by 20 metres, divided into two halves. The winner of a match is the team with the most goals at the end of the two 30-minute periods. Each goal is scored by kicking the ball into the opposing goal. The ball is handled by the players and ‘ball in hand’ movements are limited to three steps, except when dribbling. However, the attacker is allowed to jump over the goal area and take his shot before touching down again, in order to be closer to the goal.

Hockey is a team sport played by two opposing teams whose objective is to use a stick to get a ball or puck into the opponent's goal. There are many different types of hockey, including bandy, hockey, ice hockey and rink hockey.

Discipline played on a specially prepared ice rink. The aim of each team is to score goals by sending a vulcanised rubber disc, called a puck, into the opponent's goal at one end of the rink. The team consists of several lines of five players, who take turns on the ice, and a goalkeeper. The players move around on ice skates and handle the puck with a hockey stick, also known as a lacrosse stick.

This discipline pits 11 players against each other on the pitch. 10 are outfield players, responsible for attack and defence, and 1 is the goalkeeper, responsible for protecting the net. Played on a grass pitch, the players have to move the ball towards the opposing team's shooting circle, then send it into the net using a stick to score a goal. The team that scores the most goals at the end of regulation time wins.

Discipline played by two teams of 10 outdoor site in which the players each use a long stick with a net at the end to catch, carry, and throw a small ball, and try to get the ball in the other team's goal

Discipline derived from basketball, primarily played by women, in which two teams of seven players compete on a rectangular court. Each team must pass the ball and attempt to score by throwing it into elevated hoops located at either end of the court. The match lasts sixty minutes. A player in possession of the ball may hold it for only three seconds before passing it to a teammate or attempting a shot. Players are assigned specific positions that define their roles within the team and restrict their movement on the court.
Discipline in which two teams of fifteen players compete, aiming to either ground an oval-shaped ball behind the opponent’s goal line (➙ try), or to kick it between the goalposts.
Canadian discipline to designate football. Opposed two teams of eleven people, where each team tries to win by kicking a ball into the other team's gola

A sport played by two teams of nine to twelve players who alternate between offense and defense. The objective is to advance runners around four bases, called "bases," and eventually reach home plate to score as many points as possible. The sport is derived from baseball but differs in several aspects: the ball is always pitched underhand; it is larger in size; the bat has a smaller diameter; and the field is smaller.

Racquet sport played on a court entirely enclosed by walls or glass panels. The objective is to hit a small black rubber ball in such a way that the opponent cannot return it. Both players share and alternately defend the same playing area.
Discipline played by two or four players. The players position themselves at each end of a table, which has a net in the middle, and rally a small ball back and forth using paddles.

Racquet sport played either between two players (referred to as singles) or four players forming two teams of two (doubles). Players use a racket with vertical and horizontal strings to hit a rubber ball filled with air and covered with felt. The objective is to strike the ball after no more than one bounce in such a way that the opponent cannot return it within the boundaries of the court—either by hitting a winner out of the opponent's reach or by forcing them to make an error.
Aquatic sport in which two teams of seven players compete to score goals by getting a ball into the opposing team’s net.

A set of codified athletic events including sprint races (100m, 100m hurdles, 110m hurdles, 200m, 400m, 400m hurdles), middle-distance races (800m, 1500m, 3000m, 3000m steeplechase) and long-distance races (5000m, 10000m, half marathon, marathon), relay races, cross country, jumps (long jump, triple jump, high jump, pole vault), throws (shot put, hammer throw, discus, javelin), combined events, and race walking.
Included sports in which the main training was aerobic endurance training

A discipline that consists of covering a given distance as quickly as possible in a pool, without the aid of equipment. The distances in the events vary depending on the stroke. They can be 50 meters, 100 meters, and 200 meters for backstroke, butterfly, or breaststroke. Freestyle, on the other hand, can be swum in the same distances but also includes events of 400 meters, 800 meters, and 1500 meters. Additionally, there are events that combine all four strokes (in this order: butterfly, backstroke, breaststroke, freestyle) over distances of 200 meters or 400 meters
A middle-distance athletics event consisting of running 3 and 3/4 laps on an outdoor 400-meter track, and 7 and 1/2 laps on an indoor 200-meter track
A middle-distance athletics event consisting of running 7.5 laps on an outdoor 400-meter track, and 15 laps on an indoor 200-meter track.
An athletics event that is part of the long-distance races, run over a distance of 5,000 meters, which equals 12 and a half laps on an outdoor 400-meter track
A long-distance athletics event consisting of running twenty-five laps, originating from the six-mile race (9,656 meters) contested in Anglo-Saxon countries
Athletics events consisting of a cross-country race, with distances ranging from four to twelve kilometers depending on the age categories and the level of competition.
An individual running event typically held on the road, covering a distance of 42.195 kilometers
A running event held on the road, covering a distance of 21.0975 kilometers, half of a marathon.

Long-distance discipline within the sport of athletics. Although a foot race, it is different from running in that one foot must appear to be in contact with the ground at all times. Race judges carefully assess that this is maintained throughout the race. Typically held on either roads or running tracks, common distances range from 3,000 metres up to 100 kilometres.
A long-distance running race that is longer than a marathon. Ultramarathons include the following courses: 6 hours, 12 hours, 24 hours, 6 days, ultra-trail, stage races, 100 km, 50 km, etc.

Refers to continuous and rhythmic physical activity that relies primarily on the aerobic energy system. It aims to improve the efficiency of the cardiovascular and respiratory systems in supplying oxygen to working muscles over extended periods.
Any sporting activity performed on a bicycle, consisting of covering a certain distance.
Running practiced for physical fitness, on a wide variety of terrains such as woods and countryside, roads, and city streets

A speed and glide sport practiced in long, streamlined boats made of carbon fiber, wood, or composite materials. The unique feature of this discipline lies in the rower's position: facing away from the direction of travel, seated above the water level on a sliding seat called a 'slide', and propelling the boat using oars. Depending on the type of boat, the rower uses either a single sweep oar (measuring between 3.5 to 4 meters) held with both hands, or two sculling oars (about 3 meters each), one in each hand.

Disciplines of rowing. Technically, there is no heavyweight division, in the same sense that boxing or wrestling have heavyweight categories. Anything lower than 160 pounds for men and 130 pounds for women are classed as lightweight. Anything above those limits will be considered NOT lightweight and are categorized as open weight class.

Category of rowing where limits are placed on the maximum body weight of competitors. At the international level, for crew boats, the limits are: men: Crew average 70 kg, no rower over 72.5 kg ; Women: Crew average 57 kg, no rower over 59 kg ; for single sculls, the limits are 72.5 kg for men and 59 kg for women.

A free-spirited practice of running, accompanied by goals specific to a discipline. Running is part of the cult of performance: running longer or faster. For runners who practice it regularly or even intensively, it differs from jogging, which remains an occasional "Sunday" activity, to eliminate excesses or get some fresh air.

A discipline that refers to running over a distance of at least 5 kilometers. Physiologically, it is an effort primarily involving aerobic metabolic processes and requiring physical endurance capabilities.

Track races longer than sprints, ranging from 500 meters up to two miles (3,218,688 meters). The standard middle distances are the 800 meters, 1500 meters and mile run, although the 3000 meters may also be classified as a middle-distance event.
A sporting discipline consisting of three endurance events linked together in the following order: swimming, cycling and running.

A nature sport that involves designing and traveling a route by walking, not running. A hike is a walking route with an actual walking time of more than 4 hours (effort index from 26). It can be practiced on all supports allowing a pedestrian path without equipment and/or progression techniques related to mountaineering.

A sport that involves covering a set distance as quickly as possible, two by two, individually or in teams, in lanes marked on a 400-meter oval ice track, wearing clap skates. At the Olympic Games, there are six long track speed skating events for men (500 meters, 1000 meters, 1500 meters, 5000 meters, 10,000 meters, team pursuit) and six for women (500 meters, 1000 meters, 1500 meters, 3000 meters, 5000 meters, team pursuit).
All sports in which the main component of the training was strength training
A discipline practiced on a 400m ice rink. Races are held between two skaters, each in a lane. Each lap, on the straight, the skaters switch lanes to cover the same distance.

Athletic training in sports other than the athlete's usual sport. The goal is improving overall performance. It takes advantage of the particular effectiveness of one training method to negate the shortcomings of another.

Trademark for cross-training promoted by the company CrossFit Inc. In everyday language, the term CrossFit is associated with a multidisciplinary sport practice. CrossFit is built around ten athletic skills: cardiovascular and respiratory endurance, muscular endurance, strength, flexibility, power, speed, agility, coordination, balance, and accuracy."
Outdoor track and field event consisting of a straight-line sprint over a distance of 100 meters.
Track and field event consisting of a half-lap around a 400-meter outdoor track and a full lap on an indoor track
Athletic discipline consisting of throwing an implement called a javelin, made of metal, fiberglass, or carbon fiber, as far as possible

A type of running characterized by brief and intense effort aimed at developing maximum speed. It includes short sprints (50, 60, 100, 200m) and long sprints (400m), depending on the duration of the effort. The duration influences the type of energy substrates used by the muscles, and consequently, the speed that can be achieved.

A category of track and field events characterized by the throwing of a specific object: discus throw, javelin throw, hammer throw, and shot put. The size and shape of the implement vary depending on the category. The throw is measured to the nearest centimeter, from the throwing line to the first point of impact. For a throw to be valid, the athlete must release the implement while staying within the throwing area without crossing the throwing line.

High-intensity exercises for a short duration, typically ranging from a few seconds to a few minutes. This includes sprints, weightlifting (free weights or resistance machines), exercises with resistance bands, and strength training exercises (e.g., push-ups, pull-ups, squats, lunges).

Interval training aimed at improving physical conditioning through brief anaerobic exercise sessions. A workout consists of a warm-up period, approximately 6 to 10 repetitions of an exercise, and a cool-down period. Each exercise has two phases. The first phase is the intense effort phase, performed at the maximum intensity the practitioner is capable of. The second phase is the recovery phase, which can be either active (low to moderate intensity) or passive. The total duration of the session does not exceed half an hour. The ratio between effort and rest periods is typically 1:1.

Muscular Fitness includes two health-related components of fitness: muscular strength and muscular endurance. Muscular strength is the ability of a muscle group to apply a maximal force against a resistance at
one time. Muscular endurance is the ability to repeat muscle movement over a period of time.

Exercise designed to improve physical strength. It is often associated with the lifting of weights. It can also incorporate techniques such as bodyweight exercises (e.g., push-ups, pull-ups, and squats), isometrics (holding a position under tension, like planks), and plyometrics (explosive movements like jump squats and box jumps).

Physical exercises and sports in which people lift weights, often in the form of (dumbbells, barbells or machines). Other weightlifting sports include stone lifting, powerlifting, kettlebell lifting, and para powerlifting the weightlifting sport practiced at the Paralympic Games. Different weightlifting sports may be distinguished by the different ways of lifting a weight, and/or the objects lifted.
A discipline similar to weightlifting, involving lifting bars, but distinguished by its more basic movements, heavier loads, and reduced range of motion. This sport is called powerlifting in Quebec.
The activity of lifting heavy objects for exercise, especially to improve the strength of muscles and the appearance of the body
Sports where athletes are judged on the technique of their sport.
A discipline consisting of spinning a hoop, primarily around the waist, through rhythmic hip movements.
A track and field event reserved for women, consisting of running a straight 100-meter distance at maximum speed while clearing ten hurdles of 83.8 cm in height.
A track and field discipline consisting of running 400 meters, the traditional length of a lap around the track, while clearing ten hurdles. Runners must stay within the lane assigned to them
A track and field event consisting of clearing a bar placed between two vertical supports by taking off from one leg.

A discipline where, after a running start, the athlete jumps as far as possible into a sandpit. The athlete takes off from one foot, on a take-off board, just before a surface called the plasticine, which must not be touched. If the athlete steps on the plasticine, the jump is not considered valid.
A discipline where, after running a sprint of about fifty meters, the athlete uses a flexible pole to clear a horizontal bar placed several meters high without knocking it down
Discipline that consists of climbing a mountain to ski down it as quickly as possible. Alpine skiing comprises 6 events: downhill, super-G, giant slalom, slalom, alpine combined and team events.

A winter sport that combines traditional skiing with aerial acrobatics and high-speed tricks. Athletes perform jumps, spins and flips while hurtling down courses littered with obstacles such as moguls, ramps and halfpipes. It is also called freestyle skiing.

A cross-country sport involving skiing on hilly or flat slopes. The skis used are long, narrow, have no metal edges and are attached only to the front of the boot. Cross-country skis can be used in two ways: the traditional technique, known as the ‘classic’ or ‘alternating stride’, which consists of moving forward in two parallel tracks.

Discipline combines cross-country skiing and rifle shooting (22 long rifle) at a distance of 50 metres in 2 different positions: prone and standing. The interest and complexity of this discipline lies in alternating phases of intense effort with phases of calm and concentration, where precision and speed of fire are essential.

A snow sport consisting of a board, bindings (of which there are several types) and suitable boots. The position on the board is similar to that of a skateboarder: in profile, with feet placed on a line across the board, one behind the other.
A sport of precision and concentration in which competitors attempt to shoot their arrows into the centre of a target with their bow.
In rally or long-distance circuit racing, the group of drivers in a car or the group formed by the driver and the navigator responsible for guiding him.

Technique of driving a horse under human control. It can be practised as an art, a leisure activity or a sport. In this discipline, the human partner is an equine, most often a horse or pony. There are twenty-two equestrian sports, including four outdoor sports: eventing (CCE), equestrian endurance, driving and TREC.

The sport of hitting an opponent with the point or cutting edge (estoc and taille) of a white weapon on the valid parts without being hit. Three types of weapon are used: sword, sabre and foil. All three weapons are gendered: men's and women's epee, men's and women's foil and men's and women's sabre. The events are individual or team. There are twelve of them.
A precision sport played outdoors, in which a ball is hit into a hole using clubs. The aim of the game is to make as few shots as possible on a set course.
Sport in which a ball is used to knock down ten pins in one or two throws.

Athletics event in which the athlete has to cover the greatest distance by jumping either horizontally in the case of the long jump and triple jump, or vertically in the case of the high jump and pole vault.

A sport that involves using a map and a compass to run a race in search of markers indicated by a circle on the map and by an orange and white triangular grid on the ground. The challenge is to combine running with map reading and taking the initiative to choose your route between each marker.

Rifle shooting disciplines at distances of 10 m (diabolo lead), 50 m (22LR ammunition) and 300 m. The 10 m events are shot in the standing position only, while the 50 and 300 m events require either the prone position or the use of all three of the regulation prone, standing and knee positions.
The sport of sailing on water using different types of craft, from a simple float, as in windsurfing, to a real boat powered by the wind.

Discipline involving the sporting use of firearms and crossbows in an attempt to hit, with maximum accuracy and repetition, a target located at a widely varying distance. Depending on the discipline, targets are located at distances of between 10 and 300 metres (or even more for long-distance shooting) from the shooter.

The discipline of riding and performing tricks on a skateboard. Skateboarders stand on this flat wooden board, made up of a tail, a concave and a nose, on which their combined momentum and footwork enable them to perform tricks.
A sport that involves skating on roller skates or ice skates
A sport that brings together several specialities, both in the water and on the beach. These specialities are inspired by professional coastal lifesaving and the desire to ‘save better and faster’.

Kitesurfing is the sport of riding a board on the surface of a body of water while being towed by a specially adapted kite or sail. The kiteboarder wears a harness and is connected to the kite by traction lines (generally 4 or 5 in number). They steer using a bar to which the lines are attached. This bar is used as an accelerator depending on the strength of the wind. The navigation methods and rules are those of sailing.
Sports where athletes are divided by weight category with specific weight rules to face an opponent with a similar physique to theirs.

A combat sport in which two athletes, wearing protective gloves, punch each other in a boxing ring. Boxing is supervised by a referee over a series of one- to three-minute intervals called rounds. The result is decided when an opponent is deemed unable to continue by a referee, is disqualified for breaking a rule, gives up by throwing a towel, or is declared the winner or loser according to the judges' scorecards at the end of the contest.

Ancestral Japanese martial art, grouping together combat techniques developed by the samurai to defend themselves when they were unarmed. These techniques are sometimes classified into five main categories: atemi-waza: striking techniques; nage-waza: throwing techniques; ne-waza: ground techniques; kansetsu-waza: arthralgic techniques (injuring joints); shime-waza: strangulation techniques; Kuatsu: ‘return to life’ or ‘resuscitation’ technique; Kyusho: technique of the vital points of the human body.
A martial art that is also a Japanese way of life, consisting of throwing techniques, ground control, chokes and joint locks.
A combat discipline that can be considered a martial art. It belongs to the fist and foot boxing (FBO) group, meaning that the fighter essentially uses leg techniques.

Japanese martial art, although its origins are Okinawan. Karate is a martial art whose techniques aim to defend oneself and then respond with an attack targeting different parts of the body: fingers, open and closed hands, forearms, feet, elbows and knees. The fighter responds by defending or anticipating, known as Sendosei, which allows the attack to be made before the opponent's attack is made, followed by an attack in response to the opponent.

A combat sport that incorporates percussion techniques (professional foot, fist, knee and elbow), both standing and on the ground (ground and pound). There are also throwing and sweeping techniques, as well as submissions (joint locks, blood chokes).

A group of combat sports of Japanese (or more generally Asian) origin, such as judo, karate, aikido, kendo, taekwondo, viet vo dao, etc., based on a moral code (which was notably that of the samurai) and which combatants must respect.

A martial art of South Korean origin that differs from other arts in that it is highly specialised in kicking techniques. To avoid serious injury, martial artists wear a wide range of protective gear when fighting. It is the only Olympic combat sport that allows kicking.

A combat sport similar to American boxing, which allows elbow and knee strikes and is practised barefoot with gloves. Almost all blows are permitted; only blows to the head are prohibited. Among the techniques most commonly used are kicks to the neck, face and head, knee hooks to the ribs and kicks to the calves. In most matches, knee and elbow strikes win the decision. Boxers are divided into 16 weight categories. They compete in a 7.30 m2 ring surrounded by ropes held up by padded poles. A match follows a meticulous ritual. The match is preceded by the ram muay (the boxing dance), which is a tribute to the fighter's guru (khruu) and the guardian spirit of Thai boxing.

Combat sport practised with bare hands in which opponents compete hand-to-hand. There are many varieties, but the three main ones are freestyle wrestling (LL), Greco-Roman wrestling (GR) and women's wrestling (LF). The aim is to win the match either by knocking your opponent to the ground, keeping both shoulders pressed against the mat, known as a ‘fall’, or by winning on points.
Refers to all the Chinese martial arts, without any particular distinction of style or form.
